{{Infobox language family |name=Orya–Tor |region=[[New Guinea]] |familycolor=Papuan |fam1=[[North Papuan languages|North Papuan]]? |fam2=[[Tor–Kwerba–Nimboran languages|West (Tor–Kwerba–Nimboran)]] |child1=Tor |child2=''[[Orya language|Orya]]'' |glotto=toro1256 |glottorefname=Tor–Orya }}
The '''Orya–Tor''' languages are a [[language family|family]] of [[Papuan languages]] spoken in Indonesia.
==Classification== The Tor family is clearly established. Its closest relative appears to be [[Orya language|Orya]].
;Orya–Tor *[[Orya language|Orya]] (Uria) *'''Tor''' family: [[Berik language|Berik]], [[Bonerif language|Bonerif]], [[Dabe language|Dabe]]–[[Keijar language|Keijar]]–[[Betaf language|Betaf]], [[Itik language|Itik]], [[Jofotek-Bromnya language|Jofotek-Bromnya]], [[Kwesten language|Kwesten]], [[Kwinsu language|Kwinsu]], [[Mander language|Mander]], [[Maremgi language|Maremgi]] (Dineor), [[Vitou language|Vitou]]
[[Stephen Wurm]] (1975) linked Orya and the Tor languages with the [[Lakes Plain languages]], forming a branch of his [[Trans–New Guinea languages|Trans–New Guinea]] phylum. Clouse (1997) found no evidence of such a connection.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Clouse | first = Duane A. | year = 1997 | title = Towards a reconstruction and reclassification of the Lakes Plains languages of Irian Jaya | editor = Karl Franklin, ed. | journal = Papers in New Guinea Linguistics | volume = 2 | pages = 133–236 | issn = 0078-9135 | oclc = 2729642 }}</ref> [[Malcolm Ross (linguist)|Malcolm Ross]] (2005) linked them instead with part of another erstwhile branch of TNG in a [[Tor–Kwerba languages|Tor–Kwerba]] proposal. ''Glottolog'' accepts only the link with Orya as having been demonstrated.<ref name="Glottolog" />
{{anchor|Wares}}A purported Wares language is sometimes reported.<ref>{{e18|wai|Wares}}</ref> However, no such language is attested. The Wares people are not known to have a distinct language, and the language of the village of Wares is [[Mawes language|Mawes]].<ref>Hammarström (2015) Ethnologue 16/17/18th editions: a comprehensive review: online appendices</ref>
==Pronouns== The pronouns Ross reconstructs for proto-Orya–Tor are,
